</div><a id="comment-9769"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/two-sources-energy-and-using-heat#comment-9769" class="active">Energy thoughts</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://rockymountainrescue.org" rel="nofollow">DaveC</a> (not verified) on Mon, 2009-05-25 21:01.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>I read most but not all of MacKay's book, missing the section on cars. Excellent point about electric car's energy uses. MacKay is very concerned about "carbon footprint." A critical error not to count the fossil fuel use to make electricity for an electric car. </p>
<p>Where I live, electricity is about 80% from coal, 10% natural gas, 4% hydro, others minimal. Although the utilities are building mostly new gas turbine generation plants, gas is still a pretty expensive way to make electricity. Residential microturbines, especially with a mechanical linkage to the air conditioner are intriguing. I suspect they won't be competitive in the current market, because the turbines wouldn't have enough operating time to justify the capital expense. Interesting question how the economics would change with increasing fossil fuel prices. Free market resource consumption economy prevailing, I bet centralized coal fired electrical generation blocks out residential gas microturbines for decades to come. </p>
<p>Although it doesn't seem politically viable, IMHO the logical public policy approach is an increasing coal extraction task at the mine. You pretty much nailed the issue with subsidizing residential PV.</p>
<p>Great post, deserves wide reading.</p>
</div>
